Violates the principle, 'Move every piece once before you move any piece twice unless there is a tactic,' but this move does not lose a tempo because white's queen is forced to move again and keep an eye on the c2 square. My knight position improves, but white's queen position does not, so this is a free beneficial move.

Then 12...Nxc2+ wins a rook, but there likely would be tactical complications with open lines on the kingside and the a1 knight trying not to get trapped. I considered 11...Bg5 but preferred a lead in development, pressure, active pieces, and the bishop pair to being up the Exchange with complications.
